# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] In statistics, **censoring** is a condition in which the value of a measurement or observation is only partially known.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] For example, suppose a study is conducted to measure the impact of a drug on mortality rate.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] In such a study, it may be known that an individual's age at death is *at least* 75 years (but may be more).
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Such a situation could occur if the individual withdrew from the study at age 75, or if the individual is currently alive at the age of 75.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Censoring also occurs when a value occurs outside the range of a measuring instrument.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] For example, a bathroom scale might only measure up to 140 kg, after which it rolls over 0 and continues to count up from there.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] If a 160 kg individual is weighed using the scale, the observer would only know that the individual's weight is 20 mod 140 kg (in addition to 160kg, they could weigh 20kg, 300kg, 440kg, and so on).
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] The problem of censored data, in which the observed value of some variable is partially known, is related to the problem of missing data, where the observed value of some variable is unknown.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Censoring should not be confused with the related idea of truncation.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] With censoring, observations result either in knowing the exact value that applies, or in knowing that the value lies within an interval.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] With truncation, observations never result in values outside a given range: values in the population outside the range are never seen or never recorded if they are seen.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Note that in statistics, truncation is not the same as rounding.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Interval censoring can occur when observing a value requires follow-ups or inspections.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Left and right censoring are special cases of interval censoring, with the beginning of the interval at zero or the end at infinity, respectively.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Estimation methods for using left-censored data vary, and not all methods of estimation may be applicable to, or the most reliable, for all data sets.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] A common misconception with time interval data is to class as *left censored* intervals when the start time is unknown.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] In these cases, we have a lower bound on the time *interval*; thus, the data is *right censored* (despite the fact that the missing start point is to the left of the known interval when viewed as a timeline!).
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Special techniques may be used to handle censored data.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Tests with specific failure times are coded as actual failures; censored data are coded for the type of censoring and the known interval or limit.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Special software programs (often reliability oriented) can conduct a maximum likelihood estimation for summary statistics, confidence intervals, etc.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] One of the earliest attempts to analyse a statistical problem involving censored data was Daniel Bernoulli's 1766 analysis of smallpox morbidity and mortality data to demonstrate the efficacy of vaccination.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] An early paper to use the Kaplan–Meier estimator for estimating censored costs was Quesenberry et al.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] (1989), however this approach was found to be invalid by Lin et al. unless all patients accumulated costs with a common deterministic rate function over time, they proposed an alternative estimation technique known as the Lin estimator.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Reliability testing often consists of conducting a test on an item (under specified conditions) to determine the time it takes for a failure to occur.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] An analysis of the data from replicate tests includes both the times-to-failure for the items that failed and the time-of-test-termination for those that did not fail.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] An earlier model for censored regression, the tobit model, was proposed by James Tobin in 1958.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] The likelihood is the probability or probability density of what was observed, viewed as a function of parameters in an assumed model.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] To incorporate censored data points in the likelihood the censored data points are represented by the probability of the censored data points as a function of the model parameters given a model, i.e. a function of CDF(s) instead of the density or probability mass.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] Suppose we are interested in survival times, $T_{1},T_{2},\dots ,T_{n}$ , but we don't observe $T_{i}$ for all i .
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] where $f(u_{i})$ is the probability density function evaluated at $u_{i}$ , and $S(u_{i})$ is the probability that $T_{i}$ is greater than $u_{i}$ , called the *survival function*.
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] For the exponential distribution, this becomes even simpler, because the hazard rate, $\lambda$ , is constant, and $S(u)=\exp(-\lambda u)$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/censoring-statistics] This differs from the standard MLE for the exponential distribution in that the censored observations are considered only in the numerator.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The **Kaplan–Meier estimator**, also known as the **product limit estimator**, is a non-parametric statistic used to estimate the survival function from lifetime data.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] In medical research, it is often used to measure the fraction of patients living for a certain amount of time after treatment.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] In other fields, Kaplan–Meier estimators may be used to measure the length of time people remain unemployed after a job loss, the time-to-failure of machine parts, or how long fleshy fruits remain on plants before they are removed by frugivores.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Kaplan and Paul Meier, who each submitted similar manuscripts to the *Journal of the American Statistical Association*.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The journal editor, John Tukey, convinced them to combine their work into one paper, which has been cited more than 34,000 times since its publication in 1958.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] with $t_{i}$ a time when at least one event happened, *d**i* the *number of events* (e.g., deaths) that happened at time $t_{i}$ , and $n_{i}$ the *individuals known to have survived* (have not yet had an event or been censored) up to time $t_{i}$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] A plot of the Kaplan–Meier estimator is a series of declining horizontal steps which, with a large enough sample size, approaches the true survival function for that population.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The value of the survival function between successive distinct sampled observations ("clicks") is assumed to be constant.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] An important advantage of the Kaplan–Meier curve is that the method can take into account some types of censored data, particularly *right-censoring*, which occurs if a patient withdraws from a study, is lost to follow-up, or is alive without event occurrence at last follow-up.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] On the plot, small vertical tick-marks state individual patients whose survival times have been right-censored.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] When no truncation or censoring occurs, the Kaplan–Meier curve is the complement of the empirical distribution function.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] In medical statistics, a typical application might involve grouping patients into categories, for instance, those with Gene A profile and those with Gene B profile.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] In the graph, patients with Gene B die much quicker than those with Gene A.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] After two years, about 80% of the Gene A patients survive, but less than half of patients with Gene B.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] To generate a Kaplan–Meier estimator, at least two pieces of data are required for each patient (or each subject): the status at last observation (event occurrence or right-censored), and the time to event (or time to censoring).
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] If the survival functions between two or more groups are to be compared, then a third piece of data is required: the group assignment of each subject.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Let $\tau \geq 0$ be a random variable as the time that passes between the start of the possible exposure period, $t_{0}$ , and the time that the event of interest takes place, $t_{1}$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] As indicated above, the goal is to estimate the survival function S underlying $\tau$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Let $\tau _{1},\dots ,\tau _{n}\geq 0$ be independent, identically distributed random variables, whose common distribution is that of $\tau$ : $\tau _{j}$ is the random time when some event j happened.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] In particular, the information available about the timing of event j is whether the event happened before the fixed time $c_{j}$ and if so, then the actual time of the event is also available.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The challenge is to estimate $S(t)$ given this data.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Two derivations of the Kaplan–Meier estimator are shown.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Both are based on rewriting the survival function in terms of what is sometimes called **hazard**, or **mortality rates**.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] However, before doing this it is worthwhile to consider a naive estimator.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] To understand the power of the Kaplan–Meier estimator, it is worthwhile to first describe a naive estimator of the survival function.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Let $X_{k}=\mathbb {I} ({\tilde {\tau }}_{k}\geq t)$ and consider only those $k\in C(t):=\{k\,:\,c_{k}\geq t\}$ , i.e. the events for which the outcome was not censored before time t .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Let $m(t)=|C(t)|$ be the number of elements in $C(t)$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Note that the set $C(t)$ is not random and so neither is $m(t)$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Furthermore, $(X_{k})_{k\in C(t)}$ is a sequence of independent, identically distributed Bernoulli random variables with common parameter $S(t)=\operatorname {Prob} (\tau \geq t)$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] where the second equality follows because ${\tilde {\tau }}_{k}\geq t$ implies $c_{k}\geq t$ , while the last equality is simply a change of notation.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The quality of this estimate is governed by the size of $m(t)$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] This can be problematic when $m(t)$ is small, which happens, by definition, when a lot of the events are censored.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] A particularly unpleasant property of this estimator, that suggests that perhaps it is not the "best" estimator, is that it ignores all the observations whose censoring time precedes t .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] However, this information is ignored by this naive estimator.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The question is then whether there exists an estimator that makes a better use of all the data.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] This is what the Kaplan–Meier estimator accomplishes.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Note that the naive estimator cannot be improved when censoring does not take place; so whether an improvement is possible critically hinges upon whether censoring is in place.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The Kaplan–Meier estimator can be seen as a "plug-in estimator" where each $q(s)$ is estimated based on the data and the estimator of $S(t)$ is obtained as a product of these estimates.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] It remains to specify how $q(s)=1-\operatorname {Prob} (\tau =s\mid \tau \geq s)$ is to be estimated.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] (think of estimating the numerator and denominator separately in the definition of the "hazard rate" $\operatorname {Prob} (\tau =s|\tau \geq s)$ ).
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The form of the estimator stated at the beginning of the article can be obtained by some further algebra.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] This implies that we can leave out from the product defining ${\hat {S}}(t)$ all those terms where $d(s)=0$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Kaplan–Meier estimator can be derived from maximum likelihood estimation of the discrete hazard function.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] More specifically given $d_{i}$ as the number of events and $n_{i}$ the total individuals at risk at time $t_{i}$ , discrete hazard rate $h_{i}$ can be defined as the probability of an individual with an event at time $t_{i}$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] where hat is used to denote maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] More generally (for continuous as well as discrete survival distributions), the Kaplan-Meier estimator may be interpreted as a nonparametric maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The Kaplan–Meier estimator is one of the most frequently used methods of survival analysis.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The estimate may be useful to examine recovery rates, the probability of death, and the effectiveness of treatment.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] It is limited in its ability to estimate survival adjusted for covariates; parametric survival models and the Cox proportional hazards model may be useful to estimate covariate-adjusted survival.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The Kaplan-Meier estimator is directly related to the Nelson-Aalen estimator and both maximize the empirical likelihood.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] The Kaplan–Meier estimator is a statistic, and several estimators are used to approximate its variance.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] where $d_{i}$ is the number of cases and $n_{i}$ is the total number of observations, for $t_{i}<t$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Greenwood's formula is derived by noting that probability of getting $d_{i}$ failures out of $n_{i}$ cases follows a binomial distribution with failure probability $h_{i}$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] In some cases, one may wish to compare different Kaplan–Meier curves.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] This can be done by the log rank test, and the Cox proportional hazards test.
[src:kaplan-meier/kaplan-meier-estimator] Other statistics that may be of use with this estimator are pointwise confidence intervals, the Hall-Wellner band and the equal-precision band.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] The **logrank test**, or **log-rank test**, is a hypothesis test to compare the survival distributions of two samples.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] It is a nonparametric test and appropriate to use when the data are right skewed and censored (technically, the censoring must be non-informative).
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] It is widely used in clinical trials to establish the efficacy of a new treatment in comparison with a control treatment when the measurement is the time to event (such as the time from initial treatment to a heart attack).
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] The test is sometimes called the **Mantel–Cox test**.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] The logrank test can also be viewed as a time-stratified Cochran–Mantel–Haenszel test.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] The test was first proposed by Nathan Mantel and was named the *logrank test* by Richard and Julian Peto.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] The logrank test statistic compares estimates of the hazard functions of the two groups at each observed event time.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] It is constructed by computing the observed and expected number of events in one of the groups at each observed event time and then adding these to obtain an overall summary across all-time points where there is an event.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] Consider two groups of patients, e.g., treatment vs. control.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] Let $1,\ldots ,J$ be the distinct times of observed events in either group.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] Let $N_{1,j}$ and $N_{2,j}$ be the number of subjects "at risk" (who have not yet had an event or been censored) at the start of period j in the groups, respectively.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] Let $O_{1,j}$ and $O_{2,j}$ be the observed number of events in the groups at time j .
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] The null hypothesis is that the two groups have identical hazard functions, $H_{0}:h_{1}(t)=h_{2}(t)$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] Hence, under $H_{0}$ , for each group $i=1,2$ , $O_{i,j}$ follows a hypergeometric distribution with parameters $N_{j}$ , $N_{i,j}$ , $O_{j}$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] For all $j=1,\ldots ,J$ , the logrank statistic compares $O_{i,j}$ to its expectation $E_{i,j}$ under $H_{0}$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] By the central limit theorem, the distribution of each $Z_{i}$ converges to that of a standard normal distribution as J approaches infinity and therefore can be approximated by the standard normal distribution for a sufficiently large J .
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] An improved approximation can be obtained by equating this quantity to Pearson type I or II (beta) distributions with matching first four moments, as described in Appendix B of the Peto and Peto paper.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] If the two groups have the same survival function, the logrank statistic is approximately standard normal.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] A one-sided level $\alpha$ test will reject the null hypothesis if $Z>z_{\alpha }$ where $z_{\alpha }$ is the upper $\alpha$ quantile of the standard normal distribution.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] For a one-sided level $\alpha$ test with power $1-\beta$ , the sample size required is $n={\frac {4\,(z_{\alpha }+z_{\beta })^{2}}{d\log ^{2}{\lambda }}}$ where $z_{\alpha }$ and $z_{\beta }$ are the quantiles of the standard normal distribution.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] Suppose $Z_{1}$ and $Z_{2}$ are the logrank statistics at two different time points in the same study ( $Z_{1}$ earlier).
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] Calculations involving the joint distribution are needed to correctly maintain the error rate when the data are examined multiple times within a study by a Data Monitoring Committee.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] The logrank test is based on the same assumptions as the Kaplan-Meier survival curve—namely, that censoring is unrelated to prognosis, the survival probabilities are the same for subjects recruited early and late in the study, and the events happened at the times specified.
[src:kaplan-meier/logrank-test] Deviations from these assumptions matter most if they are satisfied differently in the groups being compared, for example if censoring is more likely in one group than another.
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] The **Nelson–Aalen estimator** is a non-parametric estimator of the cumulative hazard rate function in case of censored data or incomplete data.
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] It is used in survival theory, reliability engineering and life insurance to estimate the cumulative number of expected events.
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] An "event" can be the failure of a non-repairable component, the death of a human being, or any occurrence for which the experimental unit remains in the "failed" state (e.g., death) from the point at which it changed on.
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] with $d_{i}$ the number of events at time $t_{i}$ and $n_{i}$ the total individuals at risk at $t_{i}$ .
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] The curvature of the Nelson–Aalen estimator gives an idea of the hazard rate shape.
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] A concave shape is an indicator for infant mortality while a convex shape indicates wear out mortality.
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] It can be used for example when testing the homogeneity of Poisson processes.
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] It was constructed by Wayne Nelson and Odd Aalen.
[src:kaplan-meier/nelson-aalen-estimator] The Nelson-Aalen estimator is directly related to the Kaplan-Meier estimator and both maximize the empirical likelihood.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] where $m(x)$ is some deterministic function.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] Linear regression is a restricted case of nonparametric regression where $m(x)$ is assumed to be a linear function of the data.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] where the random variable U is the `noise term', with mean 0.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] Without the assumption that m belongs to a specific parametric family of functions it is impossible to get an unbiased estimate for m , however most estimators are consistent under suitable conditions.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] This is a non-exhaustive list of non-parametric models for regression.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] In Gaussian process regression, also known as Kriging, a Gaussian prior is assumed for the regression curve.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] The errors are assumed to have a multivariate normal distribution and the regression curve is estimated by its posterior mode.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] The Gaussian prior may depend on unknown hyperparameters, which are usually estimated via empirical Bayes.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] The hyperparameters typically specify a prior covariance kernel.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] In case the kernel should also be inferred nonparametrically from the data, the critical filter can be used.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] Smoothing splines have an interpretation as the posterior mode of a Gaussian process regression.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] Decision tree learning algorithms can be applied to learn to predict a dependent variable from data.
[src:kaplan-meier/nonparametric-regression] Although the original Classification And Regression Tree (CART) formulation applied only to predicting univariate data, the framework can be used to predict multivariate data, including time series.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The **survival function** is a function that gives the probability that a patient, device, or other object of interest will survive past a certain time.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The survival function is also known as the **survivor function** or **reliability function**.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The term *reliability function* is common in engineering while the term *survival function* is used in a broader range of applications, including human mortality.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The survival function is the complementary cumulative distribution function of the lifetime.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Sometimes complementary cumulative distribution functions are called survival functions in general.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Let the lifetime T be a continuous random variable describing the time to failure.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The graphs below show examples of hypothetical survival functions.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The *y*-axis is the proportion of subjects surviving.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The graphs show the probability that a subject will survive beyond time *t*.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For example, for survival function 1, the probability of surviving longer than *t* = 2 months is 0.37.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] That is, 37% of subjects survive more than 2 months.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For survival function 2, the probability of surviving longer than *t* = 2 months is 0.97.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] That is, 97% of subjects survive more than 2 months.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Median survival may be determined from the survival function: The median survival is the point where the survival function intersects the value 0.5.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For example, for survival function 2, 50% of the subjects survive 3.72 months.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Median survival cannot always be determined from the graph alone.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For example, in survival function 4, more than 50% of the subjects survive longer than the observation period of 10 months.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The survival function is one of several ways to describe and display survival data.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Another useful way to display data is a graph showing the distribution of survival times of subjects.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Olkin, page 426, gives the following example of survival data.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The number of hours between successive failures of an air-conditioning (AC) system were recorded.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The figure below shows the distribution of the time between failures.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The blue tick marks beneath the graph are the actual hours between successive AC failures.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] In this example, a curve representing the exponential distribution overlays the distribution of AC failure times; the exponential distribution approximates the distribution of AC failure times.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The distribution of failure times is the probability density function (PDF), since time can take any positive value.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] In equations, the PDF is specified as *fT*.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] If time can only take discrete values (such as 1 day, 2 days, and so on), the distribution of failure times is called the probability mass function.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Most survival analysis methods assume that time can take any positive value, and *fT* is the PDF.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] If the time between observed AC failures is approximated using the exponential function, then the exponential curve gives the probability density function, *fT*, for AC failure times.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Another useful way to display the survival data is a graph showing the cumulative failures up to each time point.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] These data may be displayed as either the cumulative number or the cumulative proportion of failures up to each time.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The graph below shows the cumulative probability (or proportion) of failures at each time for the air conditioning system.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The stairstep line in black shows the cumulative proportion of failures.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For each step there is a blue tick at the bottom of the graph indicating an observed failure time.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The smooth red line represents the exponential curve fitted to the observed data.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] A graph of the cumulative probability of failures up to each time point is called the cumulative distribution function (CDF).
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] In survival analysis, the cumulative distribution function gives the probability that the survival time is less than or equal to a specific time, *t*.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Let *T* be survival time, which is any positive number.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] A particular time is designated by the lower case letter *t*.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] where the right-hand side represents the probability that the random variable *T* is less than or equal to *t*.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] If time can take on any positive value, then the cumulative distribution function *F*(*t*) is the integral of the probability density function *f*(*t*).
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For the air-conditioning example, the graph of the CDF below illustrates that the probability that the time to failure is less than or equal to 100 hours is 0.81, as estimated using the exponential curve fit to the data.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] An alternative to graphing the probability that the failure time is *less* than or equal to 100 hours is to graph the probability that the failure time is *greater* than 100 hours.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The probability that the failure time is greater than 100 hours must be 1 minus the probability that the failure time is less than or equal to 100 hours, because total probability must sum to 1.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] This relationship is shown on the graphs below.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The graph on the left is the cumulative distribution function, which is Pr(*T* ≤ *t*).
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The graph on the right is the survival function, *S*(*t*).
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The fact that the *S*(*t*) = 1 – CDF is the reason that another name for the survival function is the complementary cumulative distribution function.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] In some cases, such as the air conditioner example, the distribution of survival times may be approximated well by a function such as the exponential distribution.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Several distributions are commonly used in survival analysis, including the exponential, Weibull, gamma, normal, log-normal, and log-logistic.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] These distributions are defined by parameters.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The normal (Gaussian) distribution, for example, is defined by the two parameters mean and standard deviation.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Survival functions that are defined by parameters are said to be parametric.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For an exponential survival distribution, the probability of failure is the same in every time interval, no matter the age of the individual or device.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] This fact leads to the "memoryless" property of the exponential survival distribution: the age of a subject has no effect on the probability of failure in the next time interval.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The exponential may be a good model for the lifetime of a system where parts are replaced as they fail.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] It may also be useful for modeling survival of living organisms over short intervals.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] It is not likely to be a good model of the complete lifespan of a living organism.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] 134) note, "If human lifetimes were exponential there wouldn't be old or young people, just lucky or unlucky ones".
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] A key assumption of the exponential survival function is that the hazard rate is constant.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] In an example given above, the proportion of men dying each year was constant at 10%, meaning that the hazard rate was constant.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The assumption of constant hazard may not be appropriate.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For example, among most living organisms, the risk of death is greater in old age than in middle age – that is, the hazard rate increases with time.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] For some diseases, such as breast cancer, the risk of recurrence is lower after 5 years – that is, the hazard rate decreases with time.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The Weibull distribution extends the exponential distribution to allow constant, increasing, or decreasing hazard rates.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] There are several other parametric survival functions that may provide a better fit to a particular data set, including normal, lognormal, log-logistic, and gamma.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] The choice of parametric distribution for a particular application can be made using graphical methods or using formal tests of fit.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] These distributions and tests are described in textbooks on survival analysis.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Lawless has extensive coverage of parametric models.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Parametric survival functions are commonly used in manufacturing applications, in part because they enable estimation of the survival function beyond the observation period.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] However, appropriate use of parametric functions requires that data are well modeled by the chosen distribution.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] If an appropriate distribution is not available, or cannot be specified before a clinical trial or experiment, then non-parametric survival functions offer a useful alternative.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] A parametric model of survival may not be possible or desirable.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] In these situations, the most common method to model the survival function is the non-parametric Kaplan–Meier estimator.
[src:kaplan-meier/survival-function] Periodic case (cohort) and death (and recovery) counts are statistically sufficient to make non-parametric maximum likelihood and least squares estimates of survival functions, without lifetime data.
